                     <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-441-victim3559 t18320906-441-viclabel2483"></join>
               
                  </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
               
                  <persName id="t18320906-441-victim3559" type="victimName">
                     MARY 
                     BONE
                  <interp inst="t18320906-441-victim3559" type="surname" value="BONE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-441-victim3559" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-441-victim3559" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
            . I am the wife of Henry Bone, who lives in <placeName id="t18320906-441-crimeloc2484">Adam and Eve-court, Whitecross-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-441-crimeloc2484" type="placeName" value="Adam and Eve-court, Whitecross-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-441-crimeloc2484" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-441-off2481 t18320906-441-crimeloc2484"></join> - he is a <rs id="t18320906-441-viclabel2485" type="occupation">private watchman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-441-victim3557 t18320906-441-viclabel2485"></join>; the prisoner rented a room of us in the next house, and had no business in my room. On Wednesday the 29th of August I had this money in a bag; there was a French shilling in it - I put it into my pocket, and put my apron over my face, and went to sleep between four and five o'clock in the afternoon; I was suddenly awoke, and the prisoner stood in the room; I said, "Oh, dear, why do you come creeping up here?" she stood a moment, then put her hands together, bent herself half double, and said,"Oh, you don't know my trouble; John is gone a walking with Mary Gray, and holding an umbrella over her;" John is her husband - I told her to go away; she went, and between nine and ten o'clock next day a person came to receive some money, and I missed it from my pocket - the prisoner came up about half an hour after I missed it, and seemed to feel for me very much, and wished very bad wishes on the person who took it; she came again about three o'clock, and said, "Oh, Mrs. Bone, my dear woman don't fret, for you will never see it any more;" I received information, and at last sent for an officer - 2l. odd of the money was found between the bricks of a cellar belonging to the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-441-person3560">
                  MARY 
                  ANN GREEN
               <interp inst="t18320906-441-person3560" type="surname" value="ANN GREEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-441-person3560" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-441-person3560" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Thomas Green. I had seen the Policeman looking about the prisoner's cellar, and shaking the mats, but a person said something which made go and take a light down into the cellar - I there picked up this bag with the money in it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-441-person3561">
                  SOPHIA 
                  GRAY
               <interp inst="t18320906-441-person3561" type="surname" value="GRAY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-441-person3561" type="given" value="SOPHIA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-441-person3561" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in the same house as Bone. On the 30th of August, at five o'clock in the afternoon, I saw the prisoner come out of her own cellar, with silver in her hand - I told a Policeman, and the cellar was searched; I saw her go to the gin-shop, and have three half-quarterns of gin, which she paid 6d. for.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-441-person3562">
                  JOSEPH 
                  GREGORY
               <interp inst="t18320906-441-person3562" type="surname" value="GREGORY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-441-person3562" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-441-person3562" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I received the bag from Green; it contains 2l. 8s. 3d., besides a French shilling - I found nothing on the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-441-person3563">
                  MARY 
                  BONE
